4320961534977, 0.014803564175963402, 0.003400282235816121, -0.02292567305266857, -0.008831092156469822, -0.005688879173249006, -0.053043268620967865, 0.02706613391637802, 0.0048154122196137905, 0.013113348744809628, -0.03273799642920494, -0.03260187432169914, 0.0014789385022595525, -0.01211510132998228, -0.02223370596766472, 0.028268568217754364, 0.0003668986901175231, 0.013623816892504692, -0.052498769015073776, 0.007373422849923372, 0.005666191689670086, -0.0020276913419365883, 0.017843684181571007, -0.00415464024990797, -0.007793140597641468, -0.00367820356041193, -0.005025271326303482, -0.01656184159219265, -0.022664766758680344, 0.010101589374244213, 0.01143447682261467, -0.0018717150669544935, -0.011088493280112743, -0.009114684537053108, -0.016198841854929924, -0.020237209275364876, 0.015007751062512398, -0.02172323875129223, 0.01191091351211071, -0.01399815920740366]], "input": ["\"ACTUAL QUANTITY IN STANDARD MIX\":\"Actual quantity in standard mix is calculated by applying the standard proportions to the actual quantity used.\"", "\"STANDARD YIELD\":\"Standard yield is the expected output from a given input, expressed as a percentage. For example, 125 kg of input yields 100 kg of output, so the standard yield is 80%.\"", "\"INTERPRETING MATERIAL MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES\":\"Interpreting material mix and yield variances involves understanding the implications of variances on cost and quality. A favourable mix variance means cheaper materials were used, while a favourable yield variance means more output was achieved than expected.\"", "\"INTER-RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN PRICE, MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES\":\"The inter-relationship between price, mix, and yield variances highlights how changes in one can affect the others. For example, cheaper materials may lead to favourable price variances but unfavourable yield variances due to lower quality.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF VARYING MATERIALS MIX\":\"An example of varying materials mix is cooking a meal at home and not following the recipe precisely, leading to a different mix of ingredients.\"", "\"REASONS FOR VARYING THE MIX\":\"Reasons for varying the mix include changes in material prices, inaccurate measurement, or intentionally using a cheaper mix to achieve a favourable mix variance.\"", "\"IMPACT OF VARYING THE MIX\":\"The impact of varying the mix includes achieving a favourable mix variance but potentially leading to lower yield and quality, which can affect long-term sales and customer satisfaction.\"", "\"ALTERNATIVE METHODS OF CONTROLLING PRODUCTION PROCESSES\":\"Alternative methods of controlling production processes involve evaluating managers on more than just material mix and yield variances to ensure quality and other important factors are considered.\"", "\"MATERIAL MIX\":", "\"CALCULATING THE SALES MIX VARIANCE\":\"Sales mix variance = (Actual sales units - Actual sales units in budgeted mix) * Standard margin\"", "\"CALCULATING THE SALES QUANTITY VARIANCE\":\"Sales quantity variance = (Actual sales in budgeted mix - Budgeted sales) * Standard margin\"", "\"SALES PRICE, MIX AND QUANTITY VARIANCES QUIZ\":\"This quiz involves calculating the sales price variance, sales mix contribution variance, and sales quantity variances for three related products Q, P, and R based on given budgeted and actual sales data.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF CONTRIBUTION MARGIN\":\"A coffee drinker decides to stop buying an expensive coffee beverage from a coffeehouse chain and switches to a cheaper drink from the same chain but continues to buy the same number of cups of coffee. This would reduce the contribution margin of the coffee seller.\"", "\"PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\":\"Planning and operational variances\" are utilized to calculate a revised budget, identify and explain factors that could and could not be allowed to revise an original budget, and calculate, identify the cause of, and explain variances for sales, materials, and labor. These variances are instrumental in distinguishing between those caused by changes in planning assumptions and those resulting from operational performance. They help in identifying whether variances are due to external factors or internal inefficiencies, thereby providing a comprehensive understanding of the underlying reasons for budget deviations.", "\"BUDGET REVISIONS\":\"BUDGET REVISIONS\" form a critical component of performance management systems. Initially, a budget is established to serve as a benchmark against which an organization's actual results can be compared to assess performance. While changes to the budget can be permitted under certain circumstances, these revisions must be meticulously controlled to prevent potential abuse. The process of revising budgets involves identifying factors that justify a revision and those that do not, as well as applying specific principles to ensure the integrity of the budgetary process. This topic is explored in a quiz that includes questions about the criteria for revising an original budget and the principles that should guide such revisions.", "\"PRINCIPLES OF BUDGET REVISIONS\":\"The principles of budget revisions include revising the budget if something occurred during the budget period that was outside the control of the manager, not revising budgets to hide inefficiencies, and ensuring that senior management approves only appropriate revisions.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}